00:14:51,624 --> 00:14:53,421
He controls
the whole liquor business...

240
00:14:53,459 --> 00:14:55,791
he's gotten
into the numbers racket.

241
00:14:58,898 --> 00:15:01,526
Dutch Schultz
is the number one...

242
00:15:01,567 --> 00:15:04,502
and he noticed me.

243
00:15:04,536 --> 00:15:06,003
l'm telling you, Becky...

244
00:15:06,038 --> 00:15:08,165
l know whatever happens
to me in my life...

245
00:15:08,207 --> 00:15:11,973
it's gonna have something
to do with Mr. Schultz.

246
00:15:12,011 --> 00:15:14,343
What are you gonna do?

247
00:15:14,380 --> 00:15:17,144
l'm gonna find him.

248
00:15:17,182 --> 00:15:20,618
How are you gonna find him?

249
00:15:20,653 --> 00:15:22,814
Don't worry, l'll find him.

250
00:15:28,861 --> 00:15:30,294
[Footsteps]

251
00:15:41,507 --> 00:15:43,532
[Footsteps]

252
00:15:52,418 --> 00:15:54,215
Hey, Harry, how you doing?

253
00:15:54,253 --> 00:15:56,585
Great. Right on schedule.

254
00:16:03,162 --> 00:16:04,493
[Dog barking]

255
00:16:44,803 --> 00:16:48,261
[Men talking
and telephones ringing]

256
00:17:32,084 --> 00:17:37,021
What's going on here?
ls this a joke?

257
00:17:37,056 --> 00:17:38,148
<i>Lulu.</i>

258
00:17:38,190 --> 00:17:41,682
[Dutch shouting]

259
00:17:41,727 --> 00:17:43,251
<i>All you have to do</i>
<i>is what you're supposed to do.</i>

260
00:17:43,295 --> 00:17:44,455
Stop dicking me around!

261
00:17:44,496 --> 00:17:47,021
All you have to do
is make the deal.

262
00:17:47,066 --> 00:17:49,626
United States of America
wants me to pay taxes. Fine!

263
00:17:49,668 --> 00:17:50,965
l'll pay the fucking taxes!

264
00:17:51,003 --> 00:17:52,868
lt's not as simple as that,
Arthur.

265
00:17:52,905 --> 00:17:55,396
Stop with the papers
and listen to me a minute!

266
00:17:55,441 --> 00:17:58,342
Look around you.
What do you see in this place?

267
00:17:58,377 --> 00:18:00,140
l got 20 desks here, right?

268
00:18:00,179 --> 00:18:03,706
How many men you see sitting
at these desks? Ten!

269
00:18:03,749 --> 00:18:05,979
Doesn't an empty desk
mean anything to you?

270
00:18:06,018 --> 00:18:08,009
Don't you understand
every week this goes on...

271
00:18:08,053 --> 00:18:09,680
that l lose money,
l lose my banks...

272
00:18:09,721 --> 00:18:12,349
l lose my men to
those dago scumbags downtown?

273
00:18:12,391 --> 00:18:14,018
<i>DlXlE: Arthur,</i>
<i>you don't seem to understand.</i>

274
00:18:14,059 --> 00:18:15,856
<i>You don't hold all the cards</i>
<i>in this situation.</i>

275
00:18:15,894 --> 00:18:18,385
What do you mean
l don't hold all the cards?

276
00:18:18,430 --> 00:18:20,159
l'm paying you
an arm and a leg, aren't l?

277
00:18:20,199 --> 00:18:23,430
l'm paying off half the judges
and cops in this town.

278
00:18:23,469 --> 00:18:25,630
What do you mean,
l don't hold the cards?

279
00:18:25,671 --> 00:18:26,968
These are my favorite.

280
00:18:27,005 --> 00:18:28,529
<i>Arthur, this is</i>
<i>the federal government.</i>

281
00:18:28,574 --> 00:18:31,372
<i>Al Capone is serving</i>
<i>41 years for tax evasion.</i>

282
00:18:31,410 --> 00:18:34,038
We'll beat it,
but it'll take a lot of money...

283
00:18:34,079 --> 00:18:37,674
and a lot of time,
you understand what l'm saying?

284
00:18:37,716 --> 00:18:39,616
[Telephone rings]

285
00:18:39,651 --> 00:18:41,050
Who are you?

286
00:18:41,086 --> 00:18:43,054
[Ring]

287
00:18:43,088 --> 00:18:45,522
A kid with luck.

288
00:18:45,557 --> 00:18:46,785
<i>DUTCH: Yeah?</i>

289
00:18:46,825 --> 00:18:49,020
Well, we could use some.

290
00:18:49,061 --> 00:18:50,824
<i>MAN:</i>
<i>We haven't heard from George.</i>

291
00:18:50,863 --> 00:18:52,387
Yeah, he's always
straight with me.

292
00:18:52,431 --> 00:18:53,796
lrving, come in here
and close the door.

293
00:18:53,832 --> 00:18:54,924
l want to talk to you.

294
00:19:04,443 --> 00:19:06,377
You forgot the coffee.

295
00:19:10,649 --> 00:19:13,447
-That's it for today.
-OK, Otto.

296
00:19:13,485 --> 00:19:16,147
-Wipe the board clean.
-Right.

297
00:19:16,188 --> 00:19:18,656
-You play the numbers, kid?
-No, sir.

298
00:19:18,690 --> 00:19:23,218
-Good. You got a mother?
-Yes, sir.

299
00:19:23,262 --> 00:19:26,595
Don't let her
play the numbers, either.

300
00:19:26,632 --> 00:19:28,759
But l'll tell you what,
l'll put you onto a sure thing.

301
00:19:28,800 --> 00:19:29,926
A horse?

302
00:19:29,968 --> 00:19:31,936
OTTO^ The world is numbers,
not horses.

303
00:19:31,970 --> 00:19:33,938
For instance, l'll tell you
how much money...

304
00:19:33,972 --> 00:19:37,499
you got in your pocket.
lf l'm right, l win it.

305
00:19:37,543 --> 00:19:39,841
lf l'm wrong,
l'm gonna match it...

306
00:19:39,878 --> 00:19:41,573
and you'll have double
what you had before.

307
00:19:41,613 --> 00:19:42,910
-How's that?
-All right.

308
00:19:42,948 --> 00:19:44,609
<i>O TTO: Count your money.</i>
<i>Don't let me see it.</i>

309
00:19:44,650 --> 00:19:46,914
-l know how much it is.
-Good.

310
00:19:46,952 --> 00:19:49,921
Now double that in your head,
and add three.

311
00:19:49,955 --> 00:19:51,547
All right.

312
00:19:51,590 --> 00:19:54,582
-Now product that by five.
-Product?

313
00:19:54,626 --> 00:19:57,754
Multiply that by five,
subtract six...

314
00:19:57,796 --> 00:19:59,525
and tell me
what you come up with.

315
00:20:01,867 --> 00:20:03,425
279.

316
00:20:03,468 --> 00:20:06,926
-You just lost 27 cents.
-Yeah!

317
00:20:13,579 --> 00:20:15,706
<i>O TTO: You might consider</i>
<i>the study of numbers.</i>

318
00:20:15,747 --> 00:20:19,979
Question--
What's 125th and 3rd?

319
00:20:20,018 --> 00:20:22,748
A street corner.
There's a candy store.

320
00:20:22,788 --> 00:20:24,551
lt's one of
our numbers houses.

321
00:20:24,590 --> 00:20:26,080
[Glass breaking]

322
00:20:32,064 --> 00:20:33,759
Son of a bitch.

323
00:20:39,338 --> 00:20:41,465
<i>MAN: Let's get out of here.</i>

324
00:20:41,506 --> 00:20:43,337
[Tires screech]

325
00:20:49,381 --> 00:20:50,939
<i>BlLLY: Otto sent me.</i>

326
00:20:50,983 --> 00:20:54,646
Ain't nothing l can do.
l work for them now.

327
00:20:54,686 --> 00:20:57,086
You tell him that, hear?

328
00:20:57,122 --> 00:21:00,751
You see what happens
when l try to do right?

329
00:21:00,792 --> 00:21:03,488
You can all go to hell,
as far as l'm concerned.

330
00:21:03,528 --> 00:21:07,931
All white men together.
You tell him that, too.

331
00:21:10,269 --> 00:21:11,759
Sounds like Jack Kelly.

332
00:21:11,803 --> 00:21:15,295
DUTCH^ See, kid?
l don't start these things.

333
00:21:15,340 --> 00:21:17,137
l'm just
this good-natured slob...

334
00:21:17,175 --> 00:21:20,667
that people think
they can walk right over.

335
00:21:20,712 --> 00:21:22,543
-You in a gang?
-No, sir.

336
00:21:22,581 --> 00:21:25,414
No? How do you expect
to learn anything?

337
00:21:25,450 --> 00:21:29,250
l hire from gangs.
That's the training ground.

338
00:21:29,288 --> 00:21:31,256
Did you ever hear
of the Frog Hollow gang?

339
00:21:31,290 --> 00:21:32,621
No, sir.

340
00:21:32,658 --> 00:21:35,058
That was the most famous
of all the Bronx gangs.

341
00:21:35,093 --> 00:21:36,720
That's where the original
Dutch Schultz came from.

342
00:21:36,762 --> 00:21:38,787
He was the toughest street
fighter that ever lived...

343
00:21:38,830 --> 00:21:41,128
so they named me Dutch Schultz
in my neighborhood.

344
00:21:41,166 --> 00:21:42,463
lt was like an honorary thing.

345
00:21:42,501 --> 00:21:45,470
Most of the gangs now
are just dumb kids.

346
00:21:45,504 --> 00:21:46,528
<i>DUTCH: ls that right?</i>

347
00:21:46,571 --> 00:21:48,198
l think,
for the real training...

348
00:21:48,240 --> 00:21:49,400
<i>DUTCH: Yeah?</i>

349
00:21:49,441 --> 00:21:51,409
You gotta go right to the top.

350
00:21:51,443 --> 00:21:53,536
<i>O TTO: You're supposed</i>
<i>to see Bo Weinberg.</i>

351
00:21:53,578 --> 00:21:54,977
Hey, Otto, you ought
to listen to this kid.

352
00:21:55,013 --> 00:21:56,275
You'll learn something.

353
00:21:56,315 --> 00:21:58,977
<i>O TTO: Thanks.</i>

354
00:22:03,422 --> 00:22:04,946
What?

355
00:22:04,990 --> 00:22:06,981
<i>O TTO: Jack Kelly's gonna be</i>
<i>at the Beakman barber shop...</i>

356
00:22:07,025 --> 00:22:08,424
<i>tomorrow morning at 9:00.</i>

357
00:22:08,460 --> 00:22:09,859
Good.

358
00:22:09,895 --> 00:22:11,988
We'll let Bo handle this.
You give him a ring.

359
00:22:12,030 --> 00:22:15,158
l tried to get Bo for two days.
l can't find him anywhere.

360
00:22:15,200 --> 00:22:16,224
Where the hell is he?

361
00:22:16,268 --> 00:22:17,997
He's supposed
to be minding the store.

362
00:22:18,036 --> 00:22:19,298
All right, kid,
l want you to be...

363
00:22:19,338 --> 00:22:22,239
at Broadway and Nassau
at 9^00 in the morning.

364
00:22:22,274 --> 00:22:23,434
BlLLY^ What do l do?

365
00:22:23,475 --> 00:22:26,842
What you do is,
you don't ask any questions.

366
00:22:26,878 --> 00:22:28,709
[Talking and laughing]

367
00:22:34,152 --> 00:22:35,642
[Police whistle blowing]

368
00:22:54,740 --> 00:22:56,105
[Horn honks]

369
00:23:02,547 --> 00:23:04,742
NEWSMAN^ Extra, extra!
Get your ''Daily Mirror!''

370
00:23:04,783 --> 00:23:08,810
-Kid.
-Mr. Berman.

371
00:23:08,854 --> 00:23:11,823
-ls that the car?
-Yes, sir.

372
00:23:14,192 --> 00:23:17,855
<i>NEWSMAN: Extra! Extra!</i>
<i>Get your ''Daily Mirror''!</i>

373
00:23:20,232 --> 00:23:21,859
-You sure that's him?
-Yes, sir.

374
00:23:21,900 --> 00:23:23,492
DUTCH^ l'm gonna have
a talk with Mr. Kelly.

375
00:23:23,535 --> 00:23:25,298
OTTO^ Not yet.
Wait'll Bo gets here.

376
00:23:25,337 --> 00:23:26,497
DUTCH^ Bo?
l don't need Bo for this.

377
00:23:26,538 --> 00:23:29,837
-Not now.
-l'm just gonna talk to him.

378
00:23:40,952 --> 00:23:47,152
<i>NEWSMAN: Gangland murder!</i>
<i>Barbershop slaying!</i>

379
00:23:47,192 --> 00:23:50,889
Gangland murder!
Barbershop slaying!

380
00:23:59,571 --> 00:24:01,698
<i>DUTCH: ''Grisly.'' There was</i>
<i>nothing grisly about it.</i>

381
00:24:01,740 --> 00:24:03,401
<i>lt was a professional</i>
<i>piece of work.</i>

382
00:24:03,442 --> 00:24:05,273
<i>Look at this. lt was neat,</i>
<i>clean, end of story...</i>

383
00:24:05,310 --> 00:24:06,436
good-bye and good luck.

384
00:24:06,478 --> 00:24:08,446
LULU^ They'll think
one of the guineas...

385
00:24:08,480 --> 00:24:10,448
or the coloreds
slit his throat.

386
00:24:10,482 --> 00:24:12,712
BO^ So, how do l know it was
the Dutchman right off the bat?

387
00:24:14,219 --> 00:24:16,813
Aw, it's good to see you, Bo.

388
00:24:16,855 --> 00:24:18,482
We thought you was dead.

389
00:24:18,523 --> 00:24:20,218
<i>BO: Well, obviously l ain't.</i>

390
00:24:20,258 --> 00:24:22,920
You couldn't wait 24 hours?

391
00:24:22,961 --> 00:24:24,792
You couldn't wait
24 hours for me...

392
00:24:24,830 --> 00:24:26,388
to come home and do this
the right way?

393
00:24:26,431 --> 00:24:27,955
Believe me, it was done right.

394
00:24:27,999 --> 00:24:29,626
OTTO^ Where were you?
l called around...

395
00:24:29,668 --> 00:24:30,760
nobody knows where you are.

396
00:24:30,802 --> 00:24:31,894
LULU^ He was with some broad.

397
00:24:31,937 --> 00:24:34,770
This was no broad.
This was a lady, a real lady.

398
00:24:34,806 --> 00:24:36,273
<i>O TTO: Where'd you take</i>
<i>this real lady...</i>

399
00:24:36,308 --> 00:24:37,866
<i>that's more important</i>
<i>than business?</i>

400
00:24:37,909 --> 00:24:39,206
Wherever it was,
she wasn't complaining.

401
00:24:39,244 --> 00:24:40,802
You could've called,
checked in.

402
00:24:40,846 --> 00:24:43,371
We never know where you are,
what you're doing.

403
00:24:43,415 --> 00:24:46,282
You're always with some dame.
We're running a business here.

404
00:24:46,318 --> 00:24:49,776
Arthur's going on trial.
You're supposed to be in charge.

405
00:24:55,160 --> 00:24:58,823
You got complaints
about the way l run things?

406
00:24:58,864 --> 00:25:01,628
DUTCH^ All Otto's saying is if
you're gonna shack up, fine...

407
00:25:01,666 --> 00:25:03,930
but we didn't know
where you was.

408
00:25:03,969 --> 00:25:06,369
What he's trying to say is,
the way you handled it...

409
00:25:06,404 --> 00:25:08,838
just wasn't too fucking smart,
that's all.

410
00:25:08,874 --> 00:25:09,966
That's all.

411
00:25:10,008 --> 00:25:11,703
Look at it this way, Arthur...

412
00:25:11,743 --> 00:25:13,973
you're the one on the lam,
and l'm the one on the town.

413
00:25:14,012 --> 00:25:16,173
Who would you rather be
at this moment?

414
00:25:16,214 --> 00:25:17,476
You know what l mean?

415
00:25:17,516 --> 00:25:20,349
[Piano playing]

416
00:25:20,619 --> 00:25:23,679
# <i>Pack up</i>
<i>all my care and woe</i> #

417
00:25:23,722 --> 00:25:26,919
# <i>Here l go,</i>
<i>singing low</i> #

418
00:25:26,958 --> 00:25:32,919
# <i>Bye bye, blackbird</i> #

419
00:25:32,964 --> 00:25:35,831
# <i>Where somebody waits for me</i> #

420
00:25:35,867 --> 00:25:38,802
# <i>Sugar's sweet, so is he</i> #

421
00:25:38,837 --> 00:25:42,705
# <i>Bye bye, blackbird...</i> #

422
00:25:42,741 --> 00:25:45,141
BO^ ls that a great tune, huh?

423
00:25:45,176 --> 00:25:46,336
[Laughs]

424
00:25:46,378 --> 00:25:50,644
Hey, kid,
take this to Mr. Schultz.

425
00:25:50,682 --> 00:25:53,742
# <i>Oh, what</i>
<i>hard luck stories</i> #

426
00:25:53,785 --> 00:25:55,480
# <i>They all hand me</i> #

427
00:25:55,520 --> 00:25:59,012
That's right, watch your toes.

428
00:25:59,057 --> 00:26:01,787
[Both laugh]

429
00:26:01,826 --> 00:26:03,123
# <i>...late tonight</i> #

430
00:26:03,161 --> 00:26:07,325
# <i>Blackbird, bye bye</i> #

431
00:26:07,365 --> 00:26:08,593
[Trumpet solo]

432
00:26:08,633 --> 00:26:11,363
BO^ l could do that easily.
Come here.

433
00:26:16,041 --> 00:26:17,702
Yeah, that's right.

434
00:26:17,742 --> 00:26:19,539
[Both laughing]

435
00:26:30,922 --> 00:26:33,356
What?

436
00:26:34,960 --> 00:26:37,258
Bo Weinberg's
double-crossing us.

437
00:26:37,295 --> 00:26:40,230
<i>O TTO: He met with</i>
<i>one of the other gangs.</i>

438
00:26:40,265 --> 00:26:43,234
<i>He offered to cut them in</i>
<i>on our whole operation.</i>

439
00:26:43,268 --> 00:26:46,066
That's a lot of shit.
l can't believe that.

440
00:26:46,104 --> 00:26:48,436
The meeting took place
on the tenth.

441
00:26:48,473 --> 00:26:51,465
Saratoga.
The Piping Rock Casino.

442
00:26:51,509 --> 00:26:53,443
The barbershop
was on the tenth...

443
00:26:53,478 --> 00:26:55,002
why we couldn't reach him.

444
00:26:55,046 --> 00:26:57,742
He said he was shacked up.

445
00:26:57,782 --> 00:27:02,014
He didn't say who with,
or where.

446
00:27:07,659 --> 00:27:10,321
No, no, no,
it doesn't make sense, Otto.

447
00:27:12,597 --> 00:27:15,065
Why would he do something
like that?

448
00:27:15,100 --> 00:27:17,534
<i>O TTO: Arthur, nobody thinks</i>
<i>you're gonna beat this rap.</i>

449
00:27:17,569 --> 00:27:20,970
<i>Word on the street</i>
<i>is that you're as good as dead.</i>

450
00:27:21,006 --> 00:27:22,405
Maybe Bo's just looking
to the future.

451
00:27:22,440 --> 00:27:25,375
What are you talking about?
You know how far back we go.

452
00:27:25,410 --> 00:27:28,243
Come on, l can't bel--
What do you want?

453
00:27:28,279 --> 00:27:32,079
Yes, sir. The bartender
asked me to give you this.

454
00:27:41,793 --> 00:27:43,454
Thank you.

455
00:27:48,266 --> 00:27:50,666
[Door closes]

456
00:27:50,702 --> 00:27:52,363
[Jazz ballad playing]

457
00:27:59,110 --> 00:28:01,044
[Whispering]

458
00:28:07,218 --> 00:28:09,209
BARTENDER^
Good night, Mr. Weinberg.

459
00:28:15,827 --> 00:28:19,092
-l'm going to the bathroom.
-OK.

460
00:28:26,538 --> 00:28:28,529
[Billy snoring]

461
00:28:38,717 --> 00:28:41,277
[Whispers] Kid.

462
00:28:41,319 --> 00:28:43,048
-Huh.
-Kid.

463
00:28:43,088 --> 00:28:44,419
Mr. Weinberg.

464
00:28:44,456 --> 00:28:46,083
Dutchman's
got you working late?

465
00:28:46,124 --> 00:28:47,614
Yes, sir.

466
00:28:50,061 --> 00:28:51,722
Where are you from, kid?

467
00:28:51,763 --> 00:28:54,561
The Bronx. Bathgate Avenue.

468
00:28:54,599 --> 00:28:56,226
Jerome Avenue.

469
00:28:56,267 --> 00:28:58,360
[Billy laughs]

470
00:29:03,608 --> 00:29:06,099
Say hello to a friend of mine
from the Bronx.

471
00:29:06,144 --> 00:29:07,805
Hello.

472
00:29:10,615 --> 00:29:12,810
Mr. Weinberg, this is $20.

473
00:29:12,851 --> 00:29:15,217
Yeah, get some sleep, kid.

474
00:29:15,253 --> 00:29:17,585
<i>BlLLY: Thanks.</i>
<i>Thanks a lot.</i>

475
00:29:23,962 --> 00:29:26,931
You know what a loyal man
is worth these days, kid?

476
00:29:26,965 --> 00:29:29,832
His weight in gold.
