686
00:43:25,202 --> 00:43:27,762
<i>DREW: You're the first Dutch.</i>

687
00:43:29,373 --> 00:43:31,204
[Cows mooing]

688
00:43:35,045 --> 00:43:37,809
<i>O TTO: All right, we have</i>
<i>28 days before the trial.</i>

689
00:43:37,848 --> 00:43:40,214
<i>That means 28 days</i>
<i>to show these folks...</i>

690
00:43:40,250 --> 00:43:42,548
<i>that Dutch Schultz</i>
<i>is one of them.</i>

691
00:43:42,586 --> 00:43:44,781
<i>Starting off,</i>
<i>we call him by his real name...</i>

692
00:43:44,822 --> 00:43:46,483
<i>Mr. Flegenheimer.</i>

693
00:43:46,523 --> 00:43:49,083
<i>Everything is quiet and polite.</i>

694
00:43:49,126 --> 00:43:51,026
<i>We're plain folks,</i>
<i>just like them...</i>

695
00:43:51,061 --> 00:43:52,824
<i>who got the government</i>
<i>on their backs.</i>

696
00:43:52,863 --> 00:43:55,593
<i>They understand that.</i>
<i>We don't get into fights.</i>

697
00:43:55,633 --> 00:43:58,101
<i>No feeling up the chambermaids.</i>

698
00:43:58,135 --> 00:43:59,932
From now on,
you eat with your mouth closed.

699
00:43:59,970 --> 00:44:02,632
-This is horse shit.
-No foul language.

700
00:44:02,673 --> 00:44:05,699
No booze, no dames, no fighting.

701
00:44:05,743 --> 00:44:08,610
This is different from the city.
These are decent people.

702
00:44:08,646 --> 00:44:11,114
<i>Make sure you act decent.</i>

703
00:44:11,148 --> 00:44:12,740
-Where's the book?
-Huh?

704
00:44:12,783 --> 00:44:14,045
l told you to bring a book.

705
00:44:14,084 --> 00:44:15,676
Either you listen,
or you go back to the Bronx.

706
00:44:15,719 --> 00:44:17,084
lt's not some kind of picnic.

707
00:44:17,121 --> 00:44:19,749
Take this to Mrs. Preston.

708
00:44:28,198 --> 00:44:29,995
ls that coffee?

709
00:44:30,034 --> 00:44:32,434
Yes.

710
00:44:33,570 --> 00:44:36,767
Hmm. Thank you.

711
00:44:47,151 --> 00:44:50,712
<i>LULU: l once met Alvin Pincus,</i>
<i>who ran with Pretty Boy Floyd.</i>

712
00:44:50,754 --> 00:44:54,019
-He always said banks was best.
-Look where he is now.

713
00:44:54,058 --> 00:44:56,083
Going for the dough
in the one place...

714
00:44:56,126 --> 00:44:57,889
that's under lock and key,
you gotta be stupid.

715
00:44:57,928 --> 00:45:01,227
-Yeah, but--
-Stay with the car, Lulu.

716
00:45:03,033 --> 00:45:04,227
You got anything to tell me
about the girl?

717
00:45:04,268 --> 00:45:05,565
Her name is Drew Preston.

718
00:45:05,602 --> 00:45:07,092
You want to explain
what she's doing here?

719
00:45:07,137 --> 00:45:08,126
We got a trial coming up.

720
00:45:08,172 --> 00:45:09,571
She's the kid's governess.

721
00:45:09,606 --> 00:45:10,903
The properties
are being observed.

722
00:45:10,941 --> 00:45:12,602
-The what?
-The properties.

723
00:45:12,643 --> 00:45:14,508
DREW^ Wait a minute.

724
00:45:14,545 --> 00:45:18,208
There. You look handsome.

725
00:45:18,248 --> 00:45:21,615
[Laughs]
That's a compliment.

726
00:45:21,652 --> 00:45:23,176
-Please come in.
-Thank you.

727
00:45:23,220 --> 00:45:24,847
lt's very nice
to make your acquaintance.

728
00:45:24,888 --> 00:45:29,052
May l introduce
my business manager, Mr. Berman?

729
00:45:29,093 --> 00:45:32,358
And Mrs. Preston, who is
the governess of my prodigy.

730
00:45:32,396 --> 00:45:34,227
lt is a pleasure to meet you.

731
00:45:44,108 --> 00:45:46,633
l'd like to open
a checking account for $10,000.

732
00:45:46,677 --> 00:45:48,076
OTTO^ And the rest
in a savings account.

733
00:45:48,112 --> 00:45:49,807
Of course.

734
00:45:49,847 --> 00:45:52,407
<i>Excuse me a moment.</i>

735
00:45:52,449 --> 00:45:55,782
l'll get my head accountant
to take care of the paperwork.

736
00:45:58,789 --> 00:46:02,384
Honey, you are looking at the
patron saint of the boondocks.

737
00:46:02,426 --> 00:46:03,950
Arthur, if l make
a tiny criticism...

738
00:46:03,994 --> 00:46:05,723
do you promise not
to get all sulky and pout?

739
00:46:05,763 --> 00:46:07,731
-What?
-lt's protege.

740
00:46:07,765 --> 00:46:11,599
-What did l say?
-Prodigy.

741
00:46:11,635 --> 00:46:14,069
lt means ''Child genius.''

742
00:46:14,104 --> 00:46:15,628
Thank you very much,
Mr. Flegenheimer.

743
00:46:15,672 --> 00:46:17,867
We don't often get famous people
in our little town.

744
00:46:17,908 --> 00:46:18,875
Yeah, l know what you mean.

745
00:46:18,909 --> 00:46:20,103
Look, if it's
all right with you...

746
00:46:20,144 --> 00:46:22,112
Mr. Berman will stay here
and work out the details.

747
00:46:22,146 --> 00:46:23,443
<i>l'm sure</i>
<i>there'll be no problem.</i>

748
00:46:23,480 --> 00:46:25,345
Say, young fella,
what's the younger generation...

749
00:46:25,382 --> 00:46:26,747
reading these days?

750
00:46:26,784 --> 00:46:28,877
Ah, yes.

751
00:46:28,919 --> 00:46:30,887
What's your name, son?

752
00:46:30,921 --> 00:46:33,685
Billy, uh...

753
00:46:33,724 --> 00:46:35,919
Bathgate.

754
00:46:35,959 --> 00:46:37,324
With youngsters like this,
we don't have to worry...

755
00:46:37,361 --> 00:46:39,659
about the future
of this country, do we?

756
00:46:39,696 --> 00:46:41,926
[Laughs] No, we don't.

757
00:46:41,965 --> 00:46:44,024
l hope to see you soon.

758
00:46:44,067 --> 00:46:45,329
Yeah, right. Come here.

759
00:46:45,369 --> 00:46:46,336
Let me see that, will you?

760
00:46:46,370 --> 00:46:47,837
What do you got there?

761
00:46:47,871 --> 00:46:50,066
What is this?
Was this your idea?

762
00:46:50,107 --> 00:46:51,438
Don't look at me, boss.

763
00:46:51,475 --> 00:46:53,170
You?
This was your brainstorm?

764
00:46:53,210 --> 00:46:54,268
Yeah.

765
00:46:54,311 --> 00:46:55,938
l love it. What'd l tell you?

766
00:46:55,979 --> 00:46:57,947
The kid's all right.
He's my prodigy.

767
00:46:57,981 --> 00:47:00,142
l know how to pick my words.
You're my prodigy.

768
00:47:00,184 --> 00:47:02,414
Get in the car.
We ain't got all day.

769
00:47:02,452 --> 00:47:04,249
Mickey, l got an inspiration.

770
00:47:04,288 --> 00:47:06,586
-lnspiration, right?
-lnspiration.

771
00:47:18,168 --> 00:47:20,136
What kind of church is this?

772
00:47:20,170 --> 00:47:23,037
lt's Catholic.

773
00:47:23,073 --> 00:47:26,065
They put a lot of work
into this place.

774
00:47:26,109 --> 00:47:28,407
''G,'' 58.

775
00:47:30,848 --> 00:47:33,146
''l,'' 1 7.

776
00:47:34,985 --> 00:47:37,476
-''G,'' 51 .
-Bingo!

777
00:47:37,521 --> 00:47:39,148
And especially Mr. Schultz...

778
00:47:39,189 --> 00:47:44,456
for so generously donating
a special cash prize of $25.

779
00:47:46,196 --> 00:47:48,289
Dollar, a dollar five,
who'll go a dollar five?

780
00:47:48,332 --> 00:47:50,197
<i>Put the ring in there.</i>
<i>lt's not frozen.</i>

781
00:47:50,234 --> 00:47:52,498
<i>-5 dollar, 10 dollar, 1 5.</i>
<i>-All righty.</i>

782
00:47:52,536 --> 00:47:53,764
Ten chickens here
in the two crates.

783
00:47:53,804 --> 00:47:56,671
Bid 25 cents anyone?
25, now 30, now 5.

784
00:47:56,707 --> 00:47:58,231
l'll give you $100
for the chickens...

785
00:47:58,275 --> 00:48:00,209
and how much
you want for the farm?

786
00:48:00,244 --> 00:48:03,077
[Car horn honks]

787
00:48:03,113 --> 00:48:05,104
[Honks]

788
00:48:08,652 --> 00:48:10,643
[Horse neighs]

789
00:48:18,028 --> 00:48:20,019
[People chattering]

790
00:48:23,033 --> 00:48:24,625
l try to talk to him,
but it's impossible.

791
00:48:24,668 --> 00:48:26,033
Sometimes he listens...

792
00:48:26,069 --> 00:48:27,696
and sometimes
he won't listen at all.

793
00:48:27,738 --> 00:48:30,002
Looks like he's going
for the farm vote.

794
00:48:31,441 --> 00:48:33,807
DUTCH^
l hope this helps for now.

795
00:48:33,303 --> 00:48:34,702
lf you need more later,
l can't promise...

796
00:48:33,843 --> 00:48:35,834
but l'll do what l can,
Mister...

797
00:48:35,278 --> 00:48:36,768
Chambers.

798
00:48:36,239 --> 00:48:38,173
-Chambers.
-Thank you, sir.

799
00:48:37,314 --> 00:48:39,373
God bless you
for what you're doing, sir.

800
00:48:38,848 --> 00:48:41,715
Mickey...who's next?

801
00:48:39,108 --> 00:48:40,268
Yeah, well, Dixie's here.

802
00:48:40,817 --> 00:48:44,446
-What are you doing here?
-Hello, Arthur.

803
00:48:40,910 --> 00:48:42,673
Come here.
Give me some more coffee.

804
00:48:42,845 --> 00:48:44,176
Why aren't you in the city?

805
00:48:42,919 --> 00:48:44,750
What are you coming up here for?

806
00:48:45,114 --> 00:48:47,048
Arthur, we need to talk.

807
00:48:45,822 --> 00:48:46,914
Why didn't you call me up?

808
00:48:47,023 --> 00:48:49,651
l didn't want to say this
on the telephone.

809
00:48:48,885 --> 00:48:50,250
Say what?

810
00:48:50,694 --> 00:48:52,423
The government turned down
our offer.

811
00:48:51,554 --> 00:48:53,545
-So double it.
-No. They won't settle.

812
00:48:52,495 --> 00:48:54,725
The prosecutor's
determined to go to trial.

813
00:48:53,863 --> 00:48:56,093
Aw, shit.
So we'll take care of him, too.

814
00:48:55,091 --> 00:48:57,025
DlXlE^ No. lt's no soap.
He can't be bought.

815
00:48:55,732 --> 00:48:57,962
He said that?
What do you want?

816
00:48:57,660 --> 00:48:58,684
l got your coffee.

817
00:48:57,701 --> 00:48:59,601
[Clatters]

818
00:48:58,835 --> 00:49:02,464
Put in on the table.
Why are you always listening?

819
00:49:01,504 --> 00:49:02,869
Will you go upstairs
and tell Mrs. Preston...

820
00:49:02,906 --> 00:49:04,498
to take you to a museum
or something?

821
00:49:03,633 --> 00:49:07,592
Get out of here!
Go to the zoo.

822
00:49:04,674 --> 00:49:07,507
Do something useful.
l need the suite.

823
00:49:06,035 --> 00:49:08,026
[Clock ticking]

824
00:49:06,710 --> 00:49:08,644
<i>BlLLY: Mrs. Preston?</i>

825
00:49:07,036 --> 00:49:09,630
Mr. Schultz
said l should wake you.

826
00:49:08,979 --> 00:49:10,469
<i>He said he needs the room...</i>

827
00:49:10,139 --> 00:49:13,438
<i>so we should go</i>
<i>to a museum or something.</i>

828
00:49:11,247 --> 00:49:14,011
Mrs. Preston, l don't think
this was such a good idea.

829
00:49:11,741 --> 00:49:14,266
Mr. Schultz didn't
say anything about this.

830
00:49:13,216 --> 00:49:14,683
One of things
about being in a gang...

831
00:49:14,644 --> 00:49:16,544
is you got to follow orders.

832
00:49:15,485 --> 00:49:17,783
<i>So far, everything</i>
<i>they asked me to do, l done it.</i>

833
00:49:16,553 --> 00:49:17,713
DREW^ Did it.

834
00:49:18,488 --> 00:49:21,821
l mean it.
l think we ought to go back.

835
00:49:18,915 --> 00:49:21,884
[Birds chirping]

836
00:49:22,158 --> 00:49:23,853
Mrs. Preston?

837
00:49:23,453 --> 00:49:25,011
<i>Mrs. Preston!</i>

838
00:49:23,560 --> 00:49:25,323
<i>Mrs. Preston!</i>

839
00:49:25,195 --> 00:49:27,755
[Breathing heavily]

840
00:49:26,522 --> 00:49:29,923
Mrs. Preston, are you all right?

841
00:49:28,791 --> 00:49:31,419
How was it when Bo died?

842
00:49:29,199 --> 00:49:31,429
Could you tell me, please?

843
00:49:31,694 --> 00:49:33,889
[Wind blowing]

844
00:49:32,068 --> 00:49:33,228
[lrving and Billy grunting]

845
00:49:36,966 --> 00:49:39,400
Unh!

846
00:49:41,304 --> 00:49:42,703
lRVlNG^ You got him?

847
00:49:41,745 --> 00:49:43,906
Hold onto him.

848
00:49:44,140 --> 00:49:46,040
Unh.

849
00:49:45,575 --> 00:49:48,305
Take care of my girl, kid.

850
00:49:47,410 --> 00:49:49,935
Don't let him hurt her.

851
00:49:49,412 --> 00:49:51,642
Get her away from him
before he hurts her.

852
00:49:49,686 --> 00:49:52,917
You hear me?

853
00:49:52,515 --> 00:49:54,779
Promise me.

854
00:49:53,857 --> 00:49:56,690
-Say it!
-l promise.

855
00:49:55,392 --> 00:49:57,826
-Unh!
-Aah!

856
00:49:56,619 --> 00:49:59,110
Mrs. Preston!

857
00:50:00,156 --> 00:50:02,818
<i>Mrs. Preston!</i>

858
00:50:02,165 --> 00:50:04,156
[Gasps]

859
00:50:04,968 --> 00:50:07,562
Did he really
ask you to protect me?

860
00:50:05,461 --> 00:50:08,259
Yes.

861
00:50:08,972 --> 00:50:11,873
lt's strange.

862
00:50:09,665 --> 00:50:12,099
l mean,
that he would think...

863
00:50:10,473 --> 00:50:13,237
that l couldn't
take care of myself.

864
00:50:12,409 --> 00:50:15,003
And you promised him you would?

865
00:50:12,568 --> 00:50:13,865
Yes.

866
00:50:14,744 --> 00:50:17,144
You always keep your promises?

867
00:50:15,238 --> 00:50:16,865
Uh-huh.

868
00:50:15,945 --> 00:50:18,812
Do you have a girlfriend?

869
00:50:17,874 --> 00:50:20,274
Yes. Yes.

870
00:50:25,148 --> 00:50:28,379
She's a very lucky girl.

871
00:50:26,956 --> 00:50:29,754
<i>O TTO: They may not be thinkers,</i>
<i>but they do think.</i>

872
00:50:27,383 --> 00:50:29,044
<i>DUTCH:</i>
<i>What is that supposed to mean?</i>

873
00:50:28,651 --> 00:50:30,346
<i>O TTO: They remember Bo.</i>

874
00:50:30,319 --> 00:50:31,616
<i>DUTCH: l remember, too.</i>

875
00:50:31,754 --> 00:50:34,154
<i>What he did</i>
<i>he brought upon himself.</i>

876
00:50:32,989 --> 00:50:34,456
<i>l am upset, too.</i>

877
00:50:34,590 --> 00:50:36,455
<i>Just because l don't</i>
<i>go around talking about it...</i>

878
00:50:36,032 --> 00:50:38,057
<i>O TTO: They liked Bo.</i>

879
00:50:37,093 --> 00:50:40,995
<i>They don't appreciate his</i>
<i>lady friend's presence here.</i>

880
00:50:40,470 --> 00:50:43,906
<i>DUTCH: That is</i>
<i>their hard luck, isn't it?</i>

881
00:50:41,197 --> 00:50:43,791
What do you think the odds are
l'll beat this rap?

882
00:50:47,403 --> 00:50:49,030
-l wouldn't bet on you.
-Why not?

883
00:50:50,473 --> 00:50:53,704
We come up here,
take the time, the trouble...

884
00:50:56,486 --> 00:50:58,420
the effort
to set things right...

885
00:51:06,088 --> 00:51:12,516
make a good impression,
and you bring along this broad.

886
00:51:06,429 --> 00:51:08,397
<i>DUTCH: All right,</i>
<i>you made your point.</i>

887
00:51:08,224 --> 00:51:10,192
[Breathes deeply]

888
00:51:10,393 --> 00:51:11,951
What?

889
00:51:12,395 --> 00:51:15,990
She was there when Bo got it.

890
00:51:14,664 --> 00:51:16,962
That is correct.

891
00:51:16,172 --> 00:51:17,833
She never should've
got on that boat...

892
00:51:16,432 --> 00:51:18,593
and she never should've got off.

893
00:51:18,000 --> 00:51:21,060
When the time comes...

894
00:51:19,836 --> 00:51:22,031
l'll smack her around
a little.

895
00:51:22,612 --> 00:51:25,274
And that's all it'll take,
l promise you.

896
00:51:23,739 --> 00:51:26,833
<i>O TTO: Don't fall in love</i>
<i>with her, Arthur.</i>

897
00:51:30,987 --> 00:51:35,083
Boy, you are
some picnic tonight.

898
00:51:33,256 --> 00:51:37,090
l said
don't fall in love with her.

899
00:51:33,282 --> 00:51:34,874
[Floorboards creak]

900
00:51:35,492 --> 00:51:36,481
[Key jangles]

901
00:51:38,988 --> 00:51:40,080
[Cocks gun]

902
00:51:39,129 --> 00:51:41,097
-Who's out there?
-Nobody.

903
00:51:41,598 --> 00:51:45,295
<i>DUTCH: Jesus Christ,</i>
<i>you scared the shit out of me.</i>

904
00:51:42,258 --> 00:51:43,919
lt's nothing.

905
00:51:43,032 --> 00:51:45,933
The citizens of Onondaga
are hard-working people...

906
00:51:44,393 --> 00:51:47,226
<i>who usually get</i>
<i>the short end of the stick...</i>

907
00:51:46,562 --> 00:51:48,325
<i>but our forefathers</i>
<i>have dealt you...</i>

908
00:51:50,099 --> 00:51:51,999
<i>a couple of cards</i>
<i>in your favor...</i>

909
00:51:52,802 --> 00:51:55,032
<i>and you people</i>
<i>know the law...</i>

910
00:51:53,476 --> 00:51:57,207
<i>isn't nothing but what</i>
<i>the people say it is.</i>

911
00:51:55,411 --> 00:51:58,039
<i>l have great confidence</i>
<i>that the people in this town...</i>

912
00:51:57,240 --> 00:52:00,732
<i>know l hold the same virtues</i>
<i>of right and wrong.</i>

913
00:51:58,181 --> 00:52:00,706
<i>And if l just may wax poetic</i>
<i>for a moment...</i>

914
00:52:00,750 --> 00:52:03,014
[Door opens, both laughing]

915
00:52:01,177 --> 00:52:03,543
Mrs. Preston,
you got to be careful.

916
00:52:03,019 --> 00:52:03,986
[Laughing]

917
00:52:05,715 --> 00:52:07,273
<i>Otto saw us.</i>

918
00:52:06,289 --> 00:52:07,847
<i>l mean it, Mrs. Preston.</i>

919
00:52:08,784 --> 00:52:11,651
You got to watch out
with these people.

920
00:52:09,926 --> 00:52:14,158
Why? [Laughs]

921
00:52:11,521 --> 00:52:14,319
They don't like anybody
to have something on them.

922
00:52:13,389 --> 00:52:16,415
[Laughs]
Do l have something on them?

923
00:52:14,624 --> 00:52:16,854
<i>Do l?</i>

924
00:52:16,392 --> 00:52:19,259
You were on the boat.

925
00:52:19,395 --> 00:52:21,659
That makes you a danger to them.

926
00:52:21,397 --> 00:52:25,697
lf l have something on them,
then so do you.

927
00:52:23,533 --> 00:52:25,091
<i>BlLLY: Yeah.</i>

928
00:52:26,903 --> 00:52:28,302
<i>You're right.</i>

929
00:52:28,538 --> 00:52:30,335
lf l don't catch on...

930
00:52:32,482 --> 00:52:34,450
then l will
have something on them.

931
00:52:34,977 --> 00:52:38,037
<i>lf Mr. Schultz decides</i>
<i>against me, that's it.</i>

932
00:52:39,515 --> 00:52:41,779
There's nothing anyone can do.

933
00:52:41,450 --> 00:52:44,942
Let me tell you something
about your Mr. Schultz.

934
00:52:43,719 --> 00:52:47,155
He is a very ordinary man.

935
00:52:46,856 --> 00:52:51,020
[Laughs]
Now you've got something on me.

936
00:52:49,432 --> 00:52:51,195
[Gunshots]

937
00:52:51,968 --> 00:52:54,596
[Chickens clucking]

938
00:52:54,030 --> 00:52:56,624
[Cocks gun]

939
00:52:58,174 --> 00:53:00,472
[Gunshots]

940
00:53:03,072 --> 00:53:05,267
Who's the better shooter?

941
00:53:06,042 --> 00:53:07,270
-lrving.
-Why?

942
00:53:07,677 --> 00:53:09,304
He got them all in there.
Nothing's wasted.

943
00:53:10,947 --> 00:53:12,346
<i>DUTCH: This ain't</i>
<i>ladies embroidery.</i>

944
00:53:13,916 --> 00:53:15,110
lt don't have to be neat.

945
00:53:17,386 --> 00:53:18,944
lf you got the time
to set it up...

946
00:53:22,325 --> 00:53:24,793
and you need a clean hit,
you send lrving...

947
00:53:25,034 --> 00:53:29,095
but if you're in a tight spot,
you want Lulu next to you.

948
00:53:27,670 --> 00:53:30,730
Boom. lt's all over
in a couple of seconds.

949
00:53:28,397 --> 00:53:31,423
[Crickets chirping]

950
00:53:30,506 --> 00:53:33,475
[Train whistle blowing
in distance]

951
00:53:33,443 --> 00:53:35,536
Guess this is about as far
from where l come from...

952
00:53:35,912 --> 00:53:38,039
as you can get.

953
00:53:41,150 --> 00:53:43,118
Where's that?

954
00:53:43,786 --> 00:53:46,016
The Bronx. Bathgate Avenue.

955
00:53:45,121 --> 00:53:46,850
<i>We live in a tenement.</i>

956
00:53:47,550 --> 00:53:49,074
Who's ''we''?

957
00:53:47,557 --> 00:53:49,354
My mom and me.

958
00:53:54,023 --> 00:53:57,891
She works in a laundry,
gets $4.00 a week.

959
00:53:57,259 --> 00:54:01,355
You probably spend
more than that for lunch.

960
00:53:58,835 --> 00:54:02,862
Maybe you don't appreciate
the position you're in.

961
00:54:02,698 --> 00:54:04,222
What position is that?

