-So, what are you?
-Public benefactor.

1202
01:03:40,609 --> 01:03:41,906
Then how is it
that you were arrested...

1203
01:03:41,944 --> 01:03:43,912
eleven times
before the age of 19?

1204
01:03:43,946 --> 01:03:46,437
DlXlE^ Those were all cases
of mistaken identity.

1205
01:03:46,481 --> 01:03:48,142
<i>REPORTER: ls this a case</i>
<i>of mistaken identity?</i>

1206
01:03:48,183 --> 01:03:50,174
No, this is minor stuff--
income tax evasion.

1207
01:03:50,219 --> 01:03:51,914
<i>REPORTER: Are you sure</i>
<i>about that, Mr. Schultz?</i>

1208
01:03:51,954 --> 01:03:53,546
<i>DUTCH: That's right.</i>
<i>l'm no gorilla.</i>

1209
01:03:53,589 --> 01:03:54,647
l never killed nobody...

1210
01:03:54,690 --> 01:03:56,157
and l never caused nobody
to get killed.

1211
01:03:56,191 --> 01:03:57,488
REPORTERS^ Mr. Schultz!

1212
01:03:57,526 --> 01:03:58,857
<i>DlXlE: That's all the questions</i>
<i>we can take.</i>

1213
01:03:58,894 --> 01:04:01,863
<i>Thank you.</i>
<i>Thank you very much.</i>

1214
01:04:01,897 --> 01:04:03,888
[Reporters asking questions]

1215
01:04:10,505 --> 01:04:12,735
[Horse neighs]

1216
01:04:15,277 --> 01:04:17,438
BAlLlFF^ All rise.

1217
01:04:18,614 --> 01:04:20,047
[Door closes]

1218
01:04:20,082 --> 01:04:21,947
<i>JUDGE: Court is in session.</i>

1219
01:04:21,984 --> 01:04:23,451
Please be seated.

1220
01:04:38,700 --> 01:04:40,634
Listen, l'll handle this.
Mr. Berman told me...

1221
01:04:40,669 --> 01:04:42,034
Mr. Schultz owns
a piece of this hotel.

1222
01:04:42,070 --> 01:04:43,628
He said they've
taken care of everything.

1223
01:04:43,672 --> 01:04:45,299
DREW^ Absolutely.

1224
01:04:45,340 --> 01:04:47,069
DOORMAN^
Welcome back, Mrs. Preston.

1225
01:04:47,109 --> 01:04:50,636
-lt's good to see you again.
-Thank you, Charles.

1226
01:04:50,679 --> 01:04:54,206
-Good afternoon, Mrs. Preston.
-Good afternoon.

1227
01:04:54,249 --> 01:04:56,513
We're always delighted
to see you, Mrs. Preston.

1228
01:04:56,551 --> 01:04:57,575
Hello, Francois.

1229
01:04:57,619 --> 01:04:59,211
l've kept your suite
available, of course...

1230
01:04:59,254 --> 01:05:01,688
and if you need anything,
please don't hesitate to ask.

1231
01:05:01,723 --> 01:05:02,883
DREW^ Thank you.

1232
01:05:02,924 --> 01:05:05,154
-Mister--
-William Bathgate.

1233
01:05:05,193 --> 01:05:07,286
Your room is just there.
And Mrs. Preston...

1234
01:05:07,329 --> 01:05:09,524
[Speaking French] Give the room
instructions to the valet.

1235
01:05:09,564 --> 01:05:11,031
-He will handle everything.
-Very good.

1236
01:05:11,066 --> 01:05:13,057
Has Mr. Preston told you
we were coming?

1237
01:05:13,101 --> 01:05:15,501
Yes, just not this soon.
When he calls...

1238
01:05:15,537 --> 01:05:17,061
<i>MAN: Good to see you again.</i>

1239
01:05:17,105 --> 01:05:19,096
[Music playing]

1240
01:05:25,580 --> 01:05:27,946
<i>WOMAN: Mark my words.</i>

1241
01:05:33,622 --> 01:05:36,648
[Band playing dance music]

1242
01:06:11,560 --> 01:06:13,551
[Unlocking door]

1243
01:06:24,906 --> 01:06:27,841
Good night, Billy.

1244
01:06:27,876 --> 01:06:29,434
Good night.

1245
01:07:02,778 --> 01:07:04,939
[Soft music playing]

1246
01:07:20,228 --> 01:07:21,661
[Earrings clatter]

1247
01:08:42,377 --> 01:08:44,368
[Telephone rings]

1248
01:08:46,348 --> 01:08:48,339
[Ring]

1249
01:08:50,418 --> 01:08:52,113
[Ring]

1250
01:08:52,153 --> 01:08:54,280
l won't tell him if you won't.

1251
01:08:54,322 --> 01:08:57,155
lt ain't funny, Mrs. Preston.

1252
01:08:57,192 --> 01:08:58,955
You think Mr. Schultz
is an ordinary man.

1253
01:08:58,994 --> 01:09:00,188
You're wrong. He's not.

1254
01:09:00,228 --> 01:09:02,594
He's a maniac.

1255
01:09:02,631 --> 01:09:03,689
What we're doing...

1256
01:09:03,732 --> 01:09:05,859
this is how people
get themselves killed.

1257
01:09:05,901 --> 01:09:07,869
And what way is that?

1258
01:09:07,903 --> 01:09:09,996
They don't stop
to calculate the odds.

1259
01:09:10,038 --> 01:09:12,404
They don't stop to think.

1260
01:09:12,440 --> 01:09:14,738
Can you calculate the odds?

1261
01:09:14,776 --> 01:09:16,437
Yeah.

1262
01:09:16,478 --> 01:09:18,673
Yeah, l used to.

1263
01:09:18,713 --> 01:09:20,442
l used to think
l had a charmed life.

1264
01:09:20,482 --> 01:09:22,712
l used to think
l was one in a million.

1265
01:09:22,751 --> 01:09:24,275
l had my wits.

1266
01:09:24,319 --> 01:09:26,549
Whatever happened,
l would be fine.

1267
01:09:26,588 --> 01:09:28,954
But now l've...

1268
01:09:28,990 --> 01:09:33,051
l've lost my wits.
l've lost my place.

1269
01:09:41,770 --> 01:09:43,761
[Telephone rings]

1270
01:09:45,006 --> 01:09:47,440
Listen to me.

1271
01:09:47,475 --> 01:09:50,035
You're smarter than he is
and braver.

1272
01:09:50,078 --> 01:09:51,409
[Ring]

1273
01:09:51,446 --> 01:09:53,914
And you'll live longer
if you're not afraid.

1274
01:09:53,949 --> 01:09:55,439
[Ring]

1275
01:09:57,352 --> 01:09:58,546
[Ring]

1276
01:09:58,587 --> 01:10:02,318
Oh, my poor Billy Bathgate.

1277
01:10:02,357 --> 01:10:04,450
[Laughs]

1278
01:10:04,492 --> 01:10:07,052
You made a promise
to protect me...

1279
01:10:07,095 --> 01:10:10,394
and l'm not making it
easy for you, am l?

1280
01:10:13,234 --> 01:10:15,395
No, ma'am, you're not.

1281
01:10:21,443 --> 01:10:23,343
[Birds chirping]

1282
01:10:27,882 --> 01:10:29,907
Are you awake?

1283
01:10:32,087 --> 01:10:33,850
Hmm?

1284
01:10:33,888 --> 01:10:36,288
Can you hear me?

1285
01:10:36,324 --> 01:10:37,916
BlLLY^ Yes.

1286
01:10:39,794 --> 01:10:41,955
l'm having breakfast
with the gang.

1287
01:10:41,997 --> 01:10:43,487
What? What?

1288
01:10:43,531 --> 01:10:47,092
No, no. My gang.

1289
01:10:47,135 --> 01:10:49,831
Here. l've written it
all down for you.

1290
01:10:49,871 --> 01:10:52,431
Meet me later at the track.

1291
01:10:57,445 --> 01:10:59,436
[Laughs]

1292
01:11:06,788 --> 01:11:08,813
[Door closes]

1293
01:11:10,892 --> 01:11:12,883
[Ring]

1294
01:11:14,295 --> 01:11:16,286
[Ring]

1295
01:11:17,799 --> 01:11:19,790
[Ring]

1296
01:11:21,603 --> 01:11:23,901
[Ring]

1297
01:11:23,938 --> 01:11:25,098
Hello?

1298
01:11:25,140 --> 01:11:27,005
Where were you last night,
the two of you?

1299
01:11:27,042 --> 01:11:28,805
We call,
there's nobody there.

1300
01:11:28,843 --> 01:11:31,073
Mr. Schultz doesn't like
that kind of thing.

1301
01:11:31,112 --> 01:11:32,909
ls there something
l ought to know about?

1302
01:11:32,947 --> 01:11:35,245
We had dinner at the Brook Club.

1303
01:11:35,283 --> 01:11:38,218
Mrs. Preston met some friends--
silly people, nothing.

1304
01:11:38,253 --> 01:11:39,515
<i>O TTO: Not for you, kid.</i>

1305
01:11:39,554 --> 01:11:41,351
Make sure she's at the track
in her box...

1306
01:11:41,389 --> 01:11:44,051
by the third race,
box number 50.

1307
01:11:44,092 --> 01:11:45,753
<i>BlLLY: Why? What for?</i>

1308
01:11:45,794 --> 01:11:48,729
<i>Don't you know when somebody's</i>
<i>trying to look out for you?</i>

1309
01:11:48,763 --> 01:11:50,560
<i>And one more thing.</i>

1310
01:11:50,598 --> 01:11:55,535
You don't have
to sit in her lap, got it?

1311
01:11:59,040 --> 01:12:00,439
[Hangs up]

1312
01:12:00,475 --> 01:12:02,807
Jesus Christ.

1313
01:12:02,844 --> 01:12:05,210
Jesus Christ.

1314
01:12:05,246 --> 01:12:09,444
Get me the Savoy Plaza Hotel
in New York City.

1315
01:12:13,588 --> 01:12:15,180
Savoy Plaza?

1316
01:12:15,223 --> 01:12:17,453
l'd like to speak to
Mr. Harvey Preston.

1317
01:12:20,195 --> 01:12:23,722
Mr. Preston, you don't know me.
l'm calling from Saratoga.

1318
01:12:23,765 --> 01:12:26,256
[People chattering,
brass band playing]

1319
01:12:31,740 --> 01:12:34,368
-A club house ticket, please.
-Yes, sir.

1320
01:12:42,117 --> 01:12:44,711
WAlTER^ Sarsaparilla?
Yes. l'll be right back.

1321
01:13:17,252 --> 01:13:18,310
Thirty-five cents.

1322
01:13:18,353 --> 01:13:20,947
Why don't you keep the change?

1323
01:13:23,525 --> 01:13:25,686
<i>MAN: OK, we got 50</i>
<i>across the board!</i>

1324
01:13:25,727 --> 01:13:27,490
<i>That's Election Day!</i>

1325
01:13:27,529 --> 01:13:29,690
[Men shouting odds]

1326
01:13:37,238 --> 01:13:39,035
Thank you very much.

1327
01:13:48,983 --> 01:13:50,211
WOMAN^ Over here!

1328
01:13:53,488 --> 01:13:55,353
John, let's go over here.

1329
01:13:55,390 --> 01:13:57,255
<i>WOMAN: Over here.</i>

1330
01:13:57,292 --> 01:13:59,260
<i>MAN: $50.</i>

1331
01:13:59,294 --> 01:14:01,421
<i>Hey, hey, hey, hey!</i>

1332
01:14:03,431 --> 01:14:05,456
[Bugle plays post]

1333
01:14:10,038 --> 01:14:12,029
[People chattering]

1334
01:14:42,670 --> 01:14:45,036
MESSENGER^ Excuse me, please.

1335
01:14:45,073 --> 01:14:46,335
Hey, hey, hey. Come here.

1336
01:14:46,374 --> 01:14:47,705
<i>MAN:</i>
<i>Oh, Harriet, over here!</i>

1337
01:14:47,742 --> 01:14:50,074
Take these flowers
down to Mrs. Preston.

1338
01:14:50,111 --> 01:14:52,079
-Mr. Wilson.
-Phil.

1339
01:14:52,113 --> 01:14:53,375
Good afternoon, ladies.

1340
01:14:56,050 --> 01:14:57,711
<i>CHARLO TTE: All of sudden</i>
<i>she just popped up...</i>

1341
01:14:57,752 --> 01:14:59,219
<i>right there</i>
<i>in the Atlantic Ocean.</i>

1342
01:14:59,254 --> 01:15:01,313
BlLLY^ l got to talk to you.

1343
01:15:01,356 --> 01:15:02,983
Something's gone wrong.

1344
01:15:03,024 --> 01:15:04,548
l think you're in
a lot of danger right now.

1345
01:15:04,592 --> 01:15:06,856
Don't be so melodramatic, Billy.

1346
01:15:06,895 --> 01:15:08,692
Mrs. Preston,
this is not a joke.

1347
01:15:08,730 --> 01:15:12,188
<i>Aren't they the most beautiful</i>
<i>things you've ever seen?</i>

1348
01:15:13,635 --> 01:15:16,502
<i>DREW: Who do you like</i>
<i>in the next race, Charlotte?</i>

1349
01:15:16,537 --> 01:15:18,164
<i>CHARLO TTE: Um...</i>

1350
01:15:21,943 --> 01:15:23,672
MESSENGER^
Flowers for Mrs. Preston.

1351
01:15:23,711 --> 01:15:26,407
[Gasps] No. Look at these.

1352
01:15:26,447 --> 01:15:28,005
[Gunshot]

1353
01:15:28,049 --> 01:15:30,415
[Crowd cheering]

1354
01:15:30,451 --> 01:15:33,284
<i>DREW: Come on.</i>

1355
01:15:33,321 --> 01:15:36,119
Come on.

1356
01:15:36,157 --> 01:15:39,251
<i>Come on, Royal Honor.</i>

1357
01:15:39,294 --> 01:15:44,027
<i>Billy, there was something</i>
<i>l wanted to tell you.</i>

1358
01:15:44,065 --> 01:15:47,125
Do you remember that man
who came to church?

1359
01:15:47,168 --> 01:15:49,033
Which man?

1360
01:15:49,070 --> 01:15:51,436
The one at
Mr. Schultz's baptism.

1361
01:15:51,472 --> 01:15:53,133
The one he respects so much.

1362
01:15:53,174 --> 01:15:55,039
Yes. Luciano.

1363
01:15:55,076 --> 01:15:58,807
l've met him before.

1364
01:15:58,846 --> 01:16:01,314
<i>BlLLY: Where? With Bo?</i>

1365
01:16:01,349 --> 01:16:04,978
<i>DREW: Mm-hmm. l was drunk.</i>

1366
01:16:05,019 --> 01:16:06,884
Did you ever tell Mr. Schultz?

1367
01:16:06,921 --> 01:16:09,947
No. You think l should have?

1368
01:16:13,594 --> 01:16:15,824
Go, Royal Honor!

1369
01:16:15,863 --> 01:16:18,457
Go! Come on!

1370
01:16:18,499 --> 01:16:19,761
<i>Go, Royal Honor!</i>

1371
01:16:19,801 --> 01:16:21,098
Go! Go! Come on!

1372
01:16:21,135 --> 01:16:23,296
Go!

1373
01:16:23,338 --> 01:16:25,169
Uhh.

1374
01:16:25,206 --> 01:16:26,468
Damn.

1375
01:16:26,507 --> 01:16:28,304
<i>WOMAN: l won! l won!</i>

1376
01:16:30,044 --> 01:16:31,306
l'm going to go bet.

1377
01:16:31,346 --> 01:16:34,338
No, l'll do it.
You stay here.

1378
01:16:36,317 --> 01:16:40,981
All right.
Put $50 to win on Phantom Fox.

1379
01:16:41,022 --> 01:16:42,546
Satisfied?

1380
01:16:42,590 --> 01:16:45,616
Don't get up.
Don't leave until l get back.

1381
01:16:45,660 --> 01:16:47,525
[Laughs]
What if l have to pee?

1382
01:16:47,562 --> 01:16:49,894
BlLLY^
l'll bring you back a can.

1383
01:16:54,736 --> 01:16:56,704
[Sighs]

1384
01:17:00,341 --> 01:17:03,401
l love you, Mrs. Preston.

1385
01:17:14,055 --> 01:17:15,420
Carter!

1386
01:17:19,293 --> 01:17:21,352
WOMAN^ Hello, Drew, dear.

1387
01:17:26,100 --> 01:17:27,397
LULU^ What's the rush?

1388
01:17:27,435 --> 01:17:29,995
-l thought l saw lrving.
-You did.

1389
01:17:30,038 --> 01:17:31,130
<i>MAN: Good to see you,</i>
<i>my darling.</i>

1390
01:17:31,172 --> 01:17:34,471
<i>Fancy meeting you here.</i>

1391
01:17:34,509 --> 01:17:36,977
DREW^ l hope so. Ha ha ha!

1392
01:17:37,011 --> 01:17:39,002
[Dramatic music playing]

1393
01:17:39,047 --> 01:17:41,140
Oh, hello.

1394
01:17:42,150 --> 01:17:43,344
MAN^ Excuse me.

1395
01:17:45,553 --> 01:17:46,611
Carter.

1396
01:17:46,654 --> 01:17:50,317
-Drew, darling.
-Carter. Ha ha!

1397
01:17:50,358 --> 01:17:52,053
<i>HARVEY: Darling!</i>

1398
01:17:53,194 --> 01:17:54,923
Harvey.

1399
01:17:54,962 --> 01:17:57,726
Harvey, what are you
doing here?

1400
01:17:57,765 --> 01:17:59,699
<i>Harvey!</i>

1401
01:17:59,734 --> 01:18:01,395
For God's sake, l've been
looking everywhere for you.

1402
01:18:01,436 --> 01:18:03,199
l got the damnedest
telephone call.

1403
01:18:03,237 --> 01:18:04,670
What the hell's going on?

1404
01:18:04,705 --> 01:18:06,104
lt's the husband.

1405
01:18:08,543 --> 01:18:09,908
Come on.

1406
01:18:23,758 --> 01:18:25,783
You should've told us.

1407
01:18:25,827 --> 01:18:28,455
How was l to know?

1408
01:18:37,338 --> 01:18:39,363
[Car engine starts]

1409
01:18:42,009 --> 01:18:44,773
-What's this all about?
-lt's the husband.

1410
01:18:44,812 --> 01:18:47,246
lRVlNG^ Come on.

1411
01:18:47,281 --> 01:18:48,873
What's with
the state troopers?

1412
01:18:48,916 --> 01:18:50,611
l don't know.
The guy's a big shot.

1413
01:18:50,651 --> 01:18:53,882
The kind of stuff
big shots do, l guess.

1414
01:19:19,080 --> 01:19:21,105
lRVlNG^
You didn't see this coming?

1415
01:19:21,149 --> 01:19:24,414
BlLLY^ Sure, like l saw it
coming with Lulu.

1416
01:19:30,124 --> 01:19:31,250
<i>lRVlNG: l don't get it.</i>

1417
01:19:31,292 --> 01:19:33,123
<i>She must've figured out</i>
<i>something.</i>

1418
01:19:33,161 --> 01:19:36,426
<i>BlLLY: Nah,</i>
<i>she didn't know nothing.</i>

1419
01:19:52,980 --> 01:19:56,313
<i>lRVlNG: Did she seem like</i>
<i>she was scared to you?</i>

1420
01:19:56,350 --> 01:19:58,511
Uh-uh.

1421
01:19:58,553 --> 01:20:01,954
She's not like ordinary people.

1422
01:20:01,989 --> 01:20:05,152
She's not scared of anything.

1423
01:20:05,193 --> 01:20:07,184
[Dramatic music playing]

1424
01:20:31,552 --> 01:20:33,611
JUDGE^
Have you reached a verdict?

1425
01:20:35,022 --> 01:20:36,614
Yes, we have, Your Honor.

1426
01:20:36,657 --> 01:20:40,423
<i>JUDGE: Will the defendant</i>
<i>please rise?</i>

1427
01:20:44,532 --> 01:20:47,092
As to the charges,
how do you find the defendant...

1428
01:20:47,134 --> 01:20:48,567
guilty or not guilty?

1429
01:20:48,603 --> 01:20:50,093
<i>MAN:</i>
<i>We, the members of the jury...</i>

1430
01:20:50,137 --> 01:20:53,129
<i>find the defendant...</i>
<i>not guilty.</i>

1431
01:20:53,174 --> 01:20:55,165
[Crowd cheers]

1432
01:20:57,011 --> 01:20:59,206
[People chattering,
piano music playing]

1433
01:20:59,247 --> 01:21:01,841
-Whoa, whoa, whoa.
-Congratulations.

1434
01:21:01,882 --> 01:21:05,181
[Slurps] Thank you.

1435
01:21:05,219 --> 01:21:07,187
-Hello, lrving, how--
-Yes. l'm good.

1436
01:21:07,221 --> 01:21:09,587
-Are you OK?
-Yeah.

1437
01:21:09,624 --> 01:21:11,114
Come on in, come on in.

1438
01:21:11,158 --> 01:21:13,956
-ls Mr. Schultz here?
-Yeah, he's upstairs.

1439
01:21:13,995 --> 01:21:16,122
l'm sorry about
what happened to your nose.

1440
01:21:16,163 --> 01:21:18,927
-Oh, don't worry.
-lt was an accident.

1441
01:21:18,966 --> 01:21:20,729
Mr. Schultz
is waiting for you upstairs.

1442
01:21:20,768 --> 01:21:22,759
He wants me to go up there?

1443
01:21:22,803 --> 01:21:25,465
Yeah, and have a good time.

1444
01:21:39,053 --> 01:21:41,920
Hey, look who's here.

1445
01:21:45,426 --> 01:21:47,690
Close the door, will you?

1446
01:21:47,728 --> 01:21:49,855
l like a little privacy.

1447
01:21:59,073 --> 01:22:01,007
Did she say anything?

1448
01:22:01,042 --> 01:22:03,670
Who?

1449
01:22:03,711 --> 01:22:06,236
Who?

1450
01:22:06,280 --> 01:22:08,475
<i>BlLLY: Mrs. Preston?</i>

1451
01:22:08,516 --> 01:22:11,679
Yeah, l think
that's the lady's name.

1452
01:22:11,719 --> 01:22:17,851
Yeah, she said
she liked you. Very much.

1453
01:22:17,892 --> 01:22:20,156
<i>She said you have class.</i>

1454
01:22:20,194 --> 01:22:22,321
She said that?

1455
01:22:23,931 --> 01:22:25,660
Well, who knows?

1456
01:22:25,700 --> 01:22:30,262
ln a better world,
in another time...

1457
01:22:35,276 --> 01:22:36,641
<i>DUTCH: What?</i>

1458
01:22:36,677 --> 01:22:38,304
They've issued
another indictment.

1459
01:22:38,346 --> 01:22:40,712
This time it's Dewey.
lt's the state.

1460
01:22:42,450 --> 01:22:44,315
DUTCH^ What is it
with this state income tax?

1461
01:22:44,352 --> 01:22:46,320
And if l beat that,
what's next, city tax?

1462
01:22:46,354 --> 01:22:48,822
And after that,
Borough of the Bronx tax?

1463
01:22:48,856 --> 01:22:50,414
And then Bathgate Avenue tax?

1464
01:22:50,458 --> 01:22:52,790
lt's not fair, Otto.

1465
01:22:52,827 --> 01:22:54,818
OTTO^ We'll wait this out
in New Jersey.

1466
01:22:54,862 --> 01:22:57,592
l'll get in touch with Hines
and work something out.

1467
01:22:57,631 --> 01:23:00,896
What does a man have to do
to deserve a break?

1468
01:23:00,935 --> 01:23:04,029
To be able to reap
the fruits of his labor?

1469
01:23:04,071 --> 01:23:06,835
l'm gonna get Dewey.
l am gonna get that bastard.

1470
01:23:06,874 --> 01:23:09,741
You can't kill Dewey.
He's too big.

1471
01:23:09,777 --> 01:23:10,869
l want to know where he lives...

1472
01:23:10,911 --> 01:23:12,344
what time
he comes out of his house.

1473
01:23:12,380 --> 01:23:13,642
OTTO^ You gotta arrange it
with the gangs.

1474
01:23:13,681 --> 01:23:15,273
You cannot just go ahead
on your own.

1475
01:23:15,316 --> 01:23:17,580
Otto!

1476
01:23:17,618 --> 01:23:21,247
Don't you ever tell me what
l can or cannot do, Otto.

1477
01:23:21,288 --> 01:23:22,915
You work for me.

1478
01:23:22,957 --> 01:23:26,620
You do as l tell you.
ls that clear?

1479
01:23:31,332 --> 01:23:33,323
[Door slams]

1480
01:23:34,935 --> 01:23:36,926
All right.

1481
01:23:36,971 --> 01:23:39,599
We'll be moving across the river
to New Jersey for a while.

1482
01:23:39,640 --> 01:23:41,505
Remember Hines?

1483
01:23:41,542 --> 01:23:43,601
From Tammany Hall, the fixer.

1484
01:23:43,644 --> 01:23:45,874
Right now he's our last chance.

1485
01:23:45,913 --> 01:23:49,872
There are 1 7 one thousand
dollar bills in there.

1486
01:23:49,917 --> 01:23:51,817
You tell him we're waiting
for an answer...

1487
01:23:51,852 --> 01:23:55,549
at the Palace Chophouse
in Newark.

1488
01:23:55,589 --> 01:23:57,955
You should've seen him
at the height of his power...

1489
01:23:57,992 --> 01:24:00,119
when he had a grip on things.

1490
01:24:00,161 --> 01:24:03,653
<i>He was a king back then.</i>

1491
01:24:05,266 --> 01:24:08,133
You never saw
the real Dutch Schultz.

1492
01:24:27,054 --> 01:24:29,318
A terrible thing
when the money won't flow.

1493
01:24:29,356 --> 01:24:31,119
l'd hoped never to see the day.

1494
01:24:31,158 --> 01:24:33,183
Nothing makes me sadder
than to refuse...

1495
01:24:33,227 --> 01:24:34,455
such a generous offer.

1496
01:24:34,495 --> 01:24:38,022
Mr. Hines, we need
your help with Dewey.

1497
01:24:38,065 --> 01:24:41,000
Mr. Dewey is a prosecutor
who wants to be president.

1498
01:24:41,035 --> 01:24:43,435
There is nothing l can do.
You tell Mr. Schultz...

1499
01:24:43,471 --> 01:24:46,338
that the business
between us is over.

1500
01:24:46,373 --> 01:24:48,341
Mr. Schultz
ain't gonna like this.

1501
01:24:48,375 --> 01:24:49,842
He's always been
very generous with you.

1502
01:24:49,877 --> 01:24:52,675
-He deserves--
-He deserves nothing.

1503
01:24:56,817 --> 01:25:00,344
<i>DUTCH: That son of a bitch.</i>
<i>That goddamn son of a bitch.</i>

1504
01:25:00,387 --> 01:25:01,684
What does he mean,
he won't take my money?

1505
01:25:01,722 --> 01:25:04,623
Suddenly my money's
not good enough for him?

1506
01:25:04,658 --> 01:25:06,125
He's a nothing, that scumbag.

1507
01:25:06,160 --> 01:25:08,651
l'll take that money
and stick it in his teeth.

1508
01:25:08,696 --> 01:25:10,891
Forget about him.
You got other problems.

1509
01:25:10,931 --> 01:25:12,523
<i>DUTCH: Don't tell me</i>
<i>to forget about him!</i>

1510
01:25:12,566 --> 01:25:13,863
You promised me Hines.

1511
01:25:13,901 --> 01:25:17,029
You told me he'd take
care of us, and now this?

1512
01:25:17,071 --> 01:25:21,974
ls this how good
your judgement is these days?

1513
01:25:25,513 --> 01:25:27,743
Listen, you don't worry
about Dewey, all right?

1514
01:25:27,781 --> 01:25:29,146
Dewey is as good as gone.

1515
01:25:29,183 --> 01:25:30,514
OTTO^ You made
an agreement with Luciano.

1516
01:25:30,551 --> 01:25:31,848
DUTCH^ l don't need
his advisement on this.

1517
01:25:31,886 --> 01:25:34,514
He drove hundreds of miles
to stand up for you in church.

1518
01:25:34,555 --> 01:25:37,217
<i>DUTCH: He didn't have the</i>
<i>decency to break bread with me.</i>

1519
01:25:37,258 --> 01:25:39,385
l don't trust that man.

1520
01:25:39,426 --> 01:25:40,586
<i>O TTO:</i>
<i>The man is sympathetic.</i>

1521
01:25:40,628 --> 01:25:42,357
Dewey's everybody's problem.

1522
01:25:42,396 --> 01:25:45,388
Luciano knows, the Dutchman
gets knocked down, he's next.

1523
01:25:45,432 --> 01:25:48,196
Meantime, l'm the one
in the frying pan!

1524
01:25:48,235 --> 01:25:50,465
Now, let me tell you
for the final time--

1525
01:25:50,504 --> 01:25:51,869
l will take Dewey out...

1526
01:25:51,906 --> 01:25:53,806
and Luciano and his men
will thank me for it.

1527
01:25:53,841 --> 01:25:55,035
Listen very carefully.

1528
01:25:55,075 --> 01:25:57,373
They will come and they will
thank me for it.

1529
01:25:57,411 --> 01:25:59,140
Mrs. Preston told me
something about him...

1530
01:25:59,179 --> 01:26:02,046
<i>about Luciano.</i>

1531
01:26:02,082 --> 01:26:06,143
She said that she thought
she'd seen him before.

1532
01:26:08,355 --> 01:26:10,687
What are you talking about?

1533
01:26:10,724 --> 01:26:13,488
She said--

1534
01:26:13,527 --> 01:26:15,995
She said she was drunk...

1535
01:26:16,030 --> 01:26:17,725
but she was
pretty sure it was him.

1536
01:26:17,765 --> 01:26:21,166
She said she was with Bo.

1537
01:26:21,201 --> 01:26:24,364
<i>DUTCH: You hear this kid?</i>

1538
01:26:24,405 --> 01:26:26,373
This is what l'm talking about.

1539
01:26:26,407 --> 01:26:29,274
This is why l say
that he is my prodigy.

1540
01:26:29,310 --> 01:26:30,402
Uhh!

1541
01:26:30,444 --> 01:26:32,344
What else did she tell you?

1542
01:26:32,379 --> 01:26:34,609
What else went on
with the two of you?!

1543
01:26:34,648 --> 01:26:36,309
-All right.
-lt's all right.

1544
01:26:36,350 --> 01:26:37,908
l'm fine. What?

1545
01:26:37,952 --> 01:26:41,388
-He's just a kid.
-l know. l'm calm.

1546
01:26:43,123 --> 01:26:45,182
[Sighs]

1547
01:26:46,660 --> 01:26:48,457
Get up.

1548
01:26:48,495 --> 01:26:50,258
What did l do?

1549
01:26:52,666 --> 01:26:54,691
That's for not telling me
sooner, kid.

1550
01:26:54,735 --> 01:26:56,396
BlLLY^ l tried.
l didn't have the chance.

1551
01:26:56,437 --> 01:26:58,905
You should've come
to me right away.

1552
01:26:58,939 --> 01:27:01,635
Even so, l didn't
hear the rest of you...

1553
01:27:01,675 --> 01:27:03,870
give me the word on
our downtown compare.

1554
01:27:03,911 --> 01:27:06,607
-That's not fair.
-Shut the fuck up, Lulu.

1555
01:27:06,647 --> 01:27:10,310
You're ugly and dumb,
and that's the truth of you.

1556
01:27:11,685 --> 01:27:13,710
Otto, get Dixie on the phone.

1557
01:27:13,754 --> 01:27:15,244
<i>l want him over here</i>
<i>right away.</i>

1558
01:27:15,289 --> 01:27:16,517
Right.

1559
01:27:16,557 --> 01:27:20,152
Fix me a rye.
Make it straight up.

1560
01:27:20,194 --> 01:27:22,719
<i>DUTCH:</i>
<i>That conniving dago scum.</i>

1561
01:27:22,763 --> 01:27:25,891
<i>Can you tell me how</i>
<i>you know what he respects?</i>

1562
01:27:25,933 --> 01:27:28,163
Me, l like something,
l tell you...

1563
01:27:28,202 --> 01:27:30,864
l don't like something,
l tell you that.

1564
01:27:30,904 --> 01:27:33,031
You cross me,
l fucking kill you.

1565
01:27:33,073 --> 01:27:34,404
Everything is clear.

1566
01:27:34,441 --> 01:27:36,841
Everything's above board
and honest, right, lrving?

1567
01:27:36,877 --> 01:27:37,901
[Telephone dings]

1568
01:27:39,880 --> 01:27:42,246
<i>l see the whole world</i>
<i>ganging up on me.</i>

1569
01:27:42,282 --> 01:27:45,012
l see the man who takes me
into his church...

1570
01:27:45,052 --> 01:27:46,781
the man who makes me
his brother...

1571
01:27:46,820 --> 01:27:49,118
and embraces me,
kisses me on the cheek...

1572
01:27:49,156 --> 01:27:53,183
is the same man
who turns my Bo against me.

1573
01:27:53,227 --> 01:27:55,195
ls that love...

1574
01:27:55,229 --> 01:27:57,857
or is that
the Sicilian kiss of death?

1575
01:27:57,898 --> 01:28:00,560
<i>l don't care how many DA's</i>
<i>come after me.</i>

1576
01:28:00,601 --> 01:28:02,569
<i>Whatever has to be done,</i>
<i>l'll do.</i>

1577
01:28:02,603 --> 01:28:04,366
<i>They think</i>
<i>that l am finished...</i>

1578
01:28:04,405 --> 01:28:07,067
but l will show them.

1579
01:28:07,107 --> 01:28:09,166
Come on, boys,
give me a smile.

1580
01:28:09,209 --> 01:28:10,676
<i>Heh heh heh.</i>

1581
01:28:10,711 --> 01:28:12,542
The Dutchman's
making a comeback.

1582
01:28:25,025 --> 01:28:27,391
What is this?
l asked for scotch.

1583
01:28:27,428 --> 01:28:29,396
Can't you do
one damn thing right?

1584
01:28:29,430 --> 01:28:30,397
But you just told me--

1585
01:28:30,431 --> 01:28:33,059
l'm fed up with you.
You're fired.

1586
01:28:33,100 --> 01:28:34,294
What?

1587
01:28:34,334 --> 01:28:37,064
l don't want to tell you twice.
Get out of here.

1588
01:28:37,104 --> 01:28:40,130
-Why?
-Know why l'm firing you?

1589
01:28:40,174 --> 01:28:42,142
You always want to know
the reasons for things...

1590
01:28:42,176 --> 01:28:44,508
always asking questions,
poking your nose...

1591
01:28:44,545 --> 01:28:45,773
into things
that don't concern you.

1592
01:28:45,813 --> 01:28:47,872
-But you--
-Always interrupting.

1593
01:28:47,915 --> 01:28:50,543
And most of all,
l'm sick of the sight of you.

1594
01:28:50,584 --> 01:28:51,573
Mr. Berman--

1595
01:28:51,618 --> 01:28:53,848
l don't want to hear
anymore, now beat it.

1596
01:28:53,887 --> 01:28:57,584
You can't fire me.
l work for Mr. Schultz.

1597
01:28:57,624 --> 01:29:00,752
Mr. Schultz does the hiring,
l do the firing.

1598
01:29:00,794 --> 01:29:04,662
Here's your severance pay.
Get lost.

1599
01:29:07,134 --> 01:29:09,159
<i>O TTO:</i>
<i>What's the matter with you?</i>

1600
01:29:09,203 --> 01:29:12,036
Can't you get it through that
thick lrish skull of yours...

1601
01:29:12,072 --> 01:29:15,064
that we don't want you?
None of us.

1602
01:29:15,109 --> 01:29:16,838
We never did.

1603
01:29:47,341 --> 01:29:48,467
[Door closes]

1604
01:29:48,509 --> 01:29:50,807
Now, there goes a kid
with luck.

1605
01:30:02,156 --> 01:30:03,817
<i>HlTMAN: Get him, Charlie!</i>

1606
01:30:03,857 --> 01:30:05,256
[Grunting]

1607
01:30:08,228 --> 01:30:09,855
Don't say a fucking thing.

1608
01:30:11,398 --> 01:30:12,797
[Screaming]

1609
01:30:32,786 --> 01:30:36,313
<i>-l heard shots!</i>
<i>-What's going on?</i>

1610
01:30:36,356 --> 01:30:38,256
Somebody call the police!

1611
01:30:38,292 --> 01:30:40,419
Come on.

1612
01:30:40,460 --> 01:30:42,792
All right, move it!

1613
01:30:42,830 --> 01:30:43,797
Come on.

1614
01:30:43,831 --> 01:30:45,389
[Car starts]

1615
01:30:45,432 --> 01:30:47,730
HlTMAN^ Go, go, go!

1616
01:30:47,768 --> 01:30:49,759
-Get down!
-Uhh!

1617
01:30:53,540 --> 01:30:54,871
Uhh!

1618
01:31:05,552 --> 01:31:07,042
Dixie?

1619
01:31:07,087 --> 01:31:09,715
What the hell'd
you bring him here for?

1620
01:31:09,756 --> 01:31:12,589
Dixie, what's going on?

1621
01:31:12,626 --> 01:31:14,958
What's the matter with you guys?

1622
01:31:14,995 --> 01:31:17,691
You double-crossed him.

1623
01:31:17,731 --> 01:31:21,292
You sold him out,
you son of a bitch!

1624
01:31:21,335 --> 01:31:25,203
Ohh! Uhh!

1625
01:31:31,411 --> 01:31:33,038
Bravo, kid.

1626
01:31:37,117 --> 01:31:39,108
<i>DlXlE: Tell these guys</i>
<i>to get rid of him.</i>

1627
01:31:39,152 --> 01:31:40,414
What's the matter, Dixie?

1628
01:31:40,454 --> 01:31:43,287
<i>He was at the chophouse.</i>
<i>He's a witness.</i>

1629
01:31:44,958 --> 01:31:46,585
Sorry, kid.

1630
01:31:46,627 --> 01:31:48,527
What are you gonna do
when he crosses you...

1631
01:31:48,562 --> 01:31:50,120
like he did Mr. Schultz?

1632
01:31:50,163 --> 01:31:51,994
-Don't worry, he won't.
-No?

1633
01:31:52,032 --> 01:31:53,897
Why don't you ask him
about the money?

1634
01:31:55,235 --> 01:31:56,293
What money?

1635
01:31:56,336 --> 01:31:58,770
He was sitting
on 5, 6 million in cash.

1636
01:31:58,805 --> 01:32:02,241
We didn't come across anything
like that, did we?

1637
01:32:02,276 --> 01:32:03,937
Lucky, we've been
all through this before.

1638
01:32:03,977 --> 01:32:05,205
They were broke.

1639
01:32:05,245 --> 01:32:07,406
They didn't have the money
for payoffs or for salaries.

1640
01:32:07,447 --> 01:32:09,415
What about the safe, huh?

1641
01:32:09,449 --> 01:32:11,610
Otto Berman had a safe.
l took a look inside.

1642
01:32:11,652 --> 01:32:13,119
lt was empty.
There was nothing in it.

1643
01:32:13,153 --> 01:32:16,520
That's not true. l saw it.
lt was full of cash.

1644
01:32:16,556 --> 01:32:19,024
<i>DlXlE: He's lying. You gonna</i>
<i>listen to some punk kid?</i>

1645
01:32:19,059 --> 01:32:21,755
He's nothing, nobody.
All he did was sweep up.

1646
01:32:21,795 --> 01:32:23,285
<i>They never let him</i>
<i>near the money.</i>

1647
01:32:23,330 --> 01:32:25,355
How come Mr. Berman
gave me this?

1648
01:32:25,399 --> 01:32:26,627
[Struggling]

1649
01:32:30,337 --> 01:32:32,305
Here, here.

1650
01:32:39,479 --> 01:32:42,812
This is a lot of money.

1651
01:32:42,849 --> 01:32:45,443
Dixie, if you're
holding out on me...

1652
01:32:45,485 --> 01:32:48,318
it's not the right way to start
a business relationship.

1653
01:32:48,355 --> 01:32:49,982
Maybe we ought to have
a little talk.

1654
01:32:50,023 --> 01:32:52,821
Charlie, Pete.

1655
01:32:52,859 --> 01:32:54,884
Lucky.

1656
01:32:56,129 --> 01:32:58,097
Lucky, l told you the truth.

1657
01:32:58,131 --> 01:33:00,065
Don't worry, Dixie.
This won't take long.

1658
01:33:10,610 --> 01:33:13,579
What am l gonna do with you?

1659
01:33:13,613 --> 01:33:16,138
You got brains, you got guts.

1660
01:33:16,183 --> 01:33:17,411
l like that...

1661
01:33:17,451 --> 01:33:19,885
but Dixie's right.
You know too much.

1662
01:33:19,920 --> 01:33:21,615
So, what am l gonna do?

1663
01:33:21,655 --> 01:33:24,590
<i>But maybe l know</i>
<i>a few things, too.</i>

1664
01:33:24,624 --> 01:33:28,993
For instance, l know
where Bathgate Avenue is...

1665
01:33:29,029 --> 01:33:31,327
l know where
you buy your cigarettes...

1666
01:33:31,365 --> 01:33:34,198
and l know the laundry
where your mother works.

1667
01:33:34,234 --> 01:33:39,604
l guess it all evens out,
don't it?

1668
01:33:40,907 --> 01:33:43,239
Take care of yourself, kid.

1669
01:33:47,180 --> 01:33:49,341
Can l have my money?

1670
01:33:59,159 --> 01:34:03,425
Sure. Why not?

1671
01:34:12,606 --> 01:34:15,268
l'll be looking in on you
from time to time...

1672
01:34:15,308 --> 01:34:17,742
just to see how
you're getting along.

1673
01:34:17,778 --> 01:34:19,439
Remember that.

1674
01:34:40,901 --> 01:34:43,699
Hey, kid, you want a ride?

1675
01:34:43,737 --> 01:34:45,534
No, thanks. l'll walk.

1676
01:34:45,572 --> 01:34:47,563
[Car starts]

